children.name: real a2
children.definition: real  sth that is real is actually what it seems to be and not false or artificialopp fake:
examples: a coat made of real fur
she had never seen areal liveelephant before.
artificial flowers can sometimes look better thanthe real thing.
is that a real diamond?
are those flowers real or artificial?
people call him baz, but his real name is reginald.

children.name: genuine b2
children.definition: genuine used about a feeling, thing, or person that really is what they seem to be :thật, đích thực
examples: for years people thought the picture was a genuine van gogh, but in fact it’s a fake.
we need a much faster system for dealing with genuine refugees.
genuine interest/concern/desire etc
the reforms are motivated by a genuine concern for the disabled.
a genuine fear of invasion
‘did he really?’ her surprise seemed genuine.

children.name: authentic c1
children.definition: authentic đích thực
examples: 1done or made in the traditional or original waysyn genuine:
authentic french food
2a painting, document, book etc that is authentic has been proved to be by a particular personsyn genuine:
an authentic work by picasso
registerin everyday english, people usually say that something isrealorthe real thingrather thanauthentic:
this isrealindian cooking.
how do you know if the picture isthe real thing?
3based on facts :
an authentic account
4used to describe a copy that is the same as, or as good as, the original :
actors dressed in authentic costumes re-enact the battle.

children.name: bona fide x
children.definition: bona fide bona fide people or things are really what they say they are, especially when this can be checked by looking at official documents : ngay tình
examples: this club is only open to bona fide members.
we have to check that he holds a bona fide qualification.
the company can only reimburse bona fide business-related expenses.

children.name: the real thing x
children.definition: the real thing sth that is the thing it is meant to be, and not a cheaper or lower quality thing:
examples: recorded music will never be as good as listening to the real thing.
i’d seen pictures of the painting, but it was very different seeing the real thing.

children.name: the genuine article x
children.definition: the genuine article sth such as a car, painting, or piece of furniture or clothing, that really is made, produced, or designed by a famous and admired person or company: thật, xịn
examples: he owns a 1947 ferrari -- the genuine article.
with paintings it is sometimes difficult to distinguish the genuine article from a good reproduction.

children.name: the real mccoy
children.definition: informal sth that is real, and not a cheaper, lower quality product: chính hiệu
examples: the moment i smelled the cigar, i knew it was the real mccoy.
the dress had a designer label, but i couldn’t tell if it was the real mccoy or a cheap imitation.

children.name: natural b1
children.definition: natural not made, caused, or changed by humans: tự nhiên
examples: it was fascinating to see the elephants in their natural environment.
the river had worn away the rock to form a natural bridge.
a pipeline carries natural gas from under the sea to the refinery inland.
the study ofthe natural world(= trees, rivers, animals, plants etc )
an area of spectacular natural beauty
natural disasters(= things such as floods or earthquake s )
death fromnatural causes
the need for natural light in offices
natural resourcesuseful or valuable substances such as oil, coal etc that exist naturally in a particular country :
zaire is a country with substantial natural resources.
naturally[adv] c1 happening or existing as part of nature and not made or done by people
a healthy body will be able to fight off the illness naturally without the use of medicine.
my hair is naturally curly.
is your hair naturally curly do you do anything to it to make it curly?
come naturally (to somebody)(= be easy for you to do because you have a natural ability )
speaking in public seems to come quite naturally to her.

children.name: wild a2
children.definition: wild wild flowers, plants, and animals are in their natural state and have not been changed or controlled by humans: hoang dã, dại
examples: wild animals/ flowers
a field full ofwild flowers
there were lots of wild flowers growing by the roadside.
in my opinion, wild animals should not be kept in zoos.
wild horse/dog/pig etc
animals both wild and domesticated
wild mushroom/garlic/rose etc
wild strawberries are much smaller than the kind you get in shops.
grow wildmọc hoang
banana trees were growing wild on the edge of the forest.

children.name: in the wild x
children.definition: in the wild if animals live in the wild, they live in their natural state, not in a place such as a farm:hoang dã, hoang vu
examples: there are only about 5000 white rhino left living in the wild.

children.name: raw b2
children.definition: raw raw sugar, silk, tobacco etc is in its natural state before or without being changed by a chemical process:thô
examples: ghana still imports both raw and processed tobacco.
the princess was wearing a dark green dress made of raw silk.
raw materialsbasic natural materials that are needed to produce things
japan depends on the outside world for virtually all of its raw materials, including oil.

children.name: having the qualities that make a particular type of person or thing real
real a2
children.definition: real use this to emphasize that someone or something has the qualities that a particular kind of person or thing should have : thực sự
examples: jane’s been a real friend to me over the years.
she’s a real tomboy!
what the country needs now is a real leader.
i remember my first real job.
simon was her first real boyfriend.

children.name: true b1
children.definition: true sb who is a true friend, believer etc is not just pretending to be one and has all of the qualities that a friend, believer etc is supposed to have:
examples: the heroine finally findstrue love.
she’s been atrue friendto me.
it’s an amateur sportin the true sense of the word(= with the exact meaning of this word ).
being a true red sox fan, he never missed a game.
true christians believe that jesus is the son of god.

children.name: proper b1
children.definition: proper british real and not sth similar which is not as good: thực thụ
examples: when are you going to get a proper job?
we don’t have a proper guest room, but you can have the sofa in the study.

children.name: not made of natural materials or substances
artificial b2
children.definition: artificial not made of natural materials or subtances : nhân tạo
examples: the juice contains no artificial coloring or flavors.
i usually use artificial sweetener in my coffee instead of sugar.
the plants can grow just as well in artificial light.
artificial light/lightingenergy is being wasted by using artificial lighting when daylight is adequate.
artificial sweeteners(= used to make food or drink taste sweeter )diet drinks contain artificial sweeteners like saccharin.
artificial colours(= used in food )i try to buy food that is free from artificial colours.
artificial flavoursice cream often has artificial flavours in it.
artificial additives(= used to give food more colour or taste )artificial additives such as colourings, sweeteners and flavour enhancers aren’t permitted in baby foods.
artificial preservatives(= used to preserve food )this jam has no artificial preservatives.
an artificial environmentanimals hate being confined in an artificial environment.
an artificial pitchbritish english the club is building a new artificial training pitch at its sports ground.
—artificially[adv] b2
food prices are being kept artificially low.
—artificiality[ uncountable ]

children.name: synthetic x
children.definition: synthetic synthetic materials or products are made using chemicalprocesses:tổng hợp
examples: many old herbal remedies have disappeared and been replaced by synthetic drugs.
synthetic chemicals
synthetic fibres/materials/fabrics
the rug is made from a mixture of wool and synthetic fibres.
synthetic rubber

children.name: man-made x
children.definition: man-made
examples: 1man-made materials and substances are not naturalsyn artificial opp natural:
fabrics made using a combination of natural and man-made fibres
the coat is 80% wool and 20% man-made fibers.
2made by people, rather than by natural processes :
europe’s largest man-made lake
the amusement park is built around a man-made lake.
current weather problems may actually be man-made, a direct result of environmental damage.

children.name: made to look real or natural
artificial b2
children.definition: artificial not real or natural, but made to look real or do the job of something real: giả
examples: on the table was a vase filled with artificial flowers.
we have one of those electric heaters with artificial logs.
it took frank a while to learn to walk with the artificial leg.
artificial flowersa vase of stiff-looking artificial flowers
artificial grassartificial grass tennis courts
artificial snowsome ski resorts use huge amounts of artificial snow.

children.name: false b2
children.definition: false not real - use this about teeth, nails, beards etc: giả
examples: nearly a third of adults in the uk have false teeth.
she was heavily made up, with false eyelashes and bright red lipstick.

children.name: fake c1
children.definition: fake fake fur/jewellery/antiques etc made to seem like real fur, jewellery etc, especially in order to make people think it is more valuable than it really is: giả
examples: her coat had a fake fur collar and cuffs.
you can buy fake gucci bags all over the city.

children.name: imitation x
children.definition: imitation use this about materials that look like sth valuable, but are actually made of sth less expensive: giả (vật liệu làm nên sản phẩm)
examples: ted was wearing an imitation leather jacket.
the dark blue sweater had imitation pearls sewn across the front.

children.name: simulated x
children.definition: simulated not real, but made to look, feel etc like a real thing, situation, or feeling: giả, mô phỏng
examples: it was one of those horrible simulated-leather ‘executive’ chairs.
models of the bridge have been tested under simulated earthquake conditions.

children.name: unnatural b2
children.definition: unnatural different from anything produced by naturesyn artificial,fake:
examples: her hair was an unnatural orange.

children.name: unspoiled c1
children.definition: unspoiled/ unspoiltuk  a place that is unspoiled is still in its beautiful natural state because no-one has built roads, buildings etc on it - use this especially about a place that has not been developed for tourists:
examples: ▪ with its largely unspoiled natural beauty, vietnam is rapidly becoming a destination for more and more foreign visitors.
▪ the path leads eventually to a vast expanse of unspoilt woodland.
▪ if you go further into the countryside, you will come across a number of unspoilt medieval walled villages.

children.name: untamed n
children.definition: untamed an animal or place that is untamed has not been trained, controlled, or changed in any way by people, so that it is still completely wild: chưa được chế ngự, chưa được dạy thuần
examples: ▪ untamed horses roamed free in the wilds of the american plains.
▪ these were the first railways, the first means of crossing wide open spaces that are still vast and untamed, even today.

children.name: processed x
children.definition: processed processedfoodhas not been left in its natural state, but has been chemically treated, especially in order to preserve it or make it look more attractive:đã chế biến
examples: processed foods may lack the vitamins and minerals found in fresh produce.
processed cheese
fully processed canned hams will not spoil and can be kept on the shelf.
